actually got this, I actually use it for this." 

722
01:11:28,240 --> 01:11:35,800
And then you reach, these are levels of fame and 
they compound over time. It's not linear, it's not  

723
01:11:35,800 --> 01:11:42,800
attributable. You can't really say... I joke about 
this, there are people who can attribute their  

724
01:11:42,800 --> 01:11:50,080
fame to one single event, Monica Lewinsky perhaps 
being good example or serial killers. All right,  

725
01:11:50,080 --> 01:11:55,840
okay. "If I hadn't killed all those people, no one 
would've heard of me." There are people for whom  

726
01:11:55,840 --> 01:12:03,400
fame is attributable, but for most people it's 
a whole what you might call amalgam of different  

727
01:12:03,400 --> 01:12:10,800
activities going back years. And actually in 
many cases we ask consumers, "How did you hear  

728
01:12:10,800 --> 01:12:17,360
about this?" They don't actually know. They'll 
always put TV or something online, but actually  

729
01:12:17,360 --> 01:12:21,280
they don't know how they heard about it. They 
just heard about it. And we know that people's  

730
01:12:21,280 --> 01:12:26,720
brains react completely differently in terms of 
their level of comfort with things they've heard  

731
01:12:26,720 --> 01:12:31,840
of before versus things that are completely 
new. It's almost similar to the heuristic of,  

732
01:12:33,440 --> 01:12:38,400
is everybody else eating this? Have I eaten it 
before and have I heard of people eating this? 

733
01:12:41,000 --> 01:12:46,240
It's part of that same package of right 
in the motherboard at human psychology.  

734
01:12:46,240 --> 01:12:52,880
So fame is completely, it basically changes the 
rules for everything. When your chief executive  

735
01:12:52,880 --> 01:12:57,920
rings somebody up, they probably call back. If 
you're a famous company, if he's heard of you  

736
01:12:57,920 --> 01:13:03,240
or she's heard of you, she'll call back. If they 
haven't heard of you, they probably won't call  

737
01:13:03,240 --> 01:13:08,840
back. What's that worth? What's it possible? It's 
impossible to quantify the value of fame. People  

738
01:13:08,840 --> 01:13:13,000
come and work for you for less money. People 
actually apply to you without you having to  

739
01:13:13,000 --> 01:13:18,000
find them. People stay longer, customers come to 
you and give you the benefit of the doubt. You're  

740
01:13:18,000 --> 01:13:25,160
allowed to cock up once if you're famous. People 
will give you, if you've got a great brand, the  

741
01:13:25,160 --> 01:13:31,120
best definition of a brand is from the guy who's 
called Eric Johnson, I think, who wrote the book,  

742
01:13:31,120 --> 01:13:40,200
Blind Sight and he's also written a book called 
Brands That Mean Business. It's a great book.  

743
01:13:40,200 --> 01:13:47,000
It deserves to be much more famous actually.
And there's a sentence in that book which says,  

744
01:13:47,000 --> 01:13:55,440
"Having a great brand means you get to play the 
game of capitalism on easy mode." And I genuinely  

745
01:13:55,440 --> 01:13:58,920
can't think of a better definition than 
that. Now, the point about playing on easy  

746
01:13:58,920 --> 01:14:03,800
mode is can you quantify the value of that? 
Well, no. Because you don't know what your  

747
01:14:03,800 --> 01:14:09,280
score would've been if you were playing on 
hard mode or psycho mode. I'm not a gamer,  

748
01:14:09,280 --> 01:14:18,440
but you know what I mean. Okay. Can you also say 
which of your various activities contributed to  

749
01:14:18,440 --> 01:14:24,040
the building of that great brand? Well, no, you 
can't because it's actually not even an amalgam  

750
01:14:24,040 --> 01:14:30,400
of things. It's actually a concatenation.
There are a host of elements here which are  

751
01:14:30,400 --> 01:14:35,840
catalytic. They're not linear. And that's the 
other thing, which is that because it's not  

752
01:14:35,840 --> 01:14:45,360
linear, attempts to evaluate advertising on 
short-term transactional metrics will always  

753
01:14:45,360 --> 01:14:52,960
grotesquely undervalue the contribution of that 
activity to your ultimate business success. It's a  

754
01:14:52,960 --> 01:14:58,240
bit like when I first got a pension for the first 
few years, brand building is a bit like a pension.  

755
01:14:58,800 --> 01:15:03,440
For the first few years I had a pension. Oh God, 
I'm paying this guy a few hundred quid a month and  

756
01:15:03,440 --> 01:15:08,800
look, half it's gone in commission and there was a 
lot of work and I'd rather have the money to have  

757
01:15:08,800 --> 01:15:14,320
an Indian meal. I don't know why I'm doing this. 
Oh look, it's hardly gone up at all. What a bore,  

758
01:15:14,320 --> 01:15:19,280
what a waste of time. I thought that for 
about three years. I'm 58 now and I've got  

759
01:15:19,280 --> 01:15:24,960
a pension and I go, "Where did all this money 
come from? I don't remember paying this." 

760
01:15:25,640 --> 01:15:32,200
It really is like that. It's a compounding effect. 
And everybody effectively, because we have finance  

761
01:15:32,200 --> 01:15:37,200
and ROI and all those things, everybody's 
using addition, multiplication, subtraction,  

762
01:15:37,200 --> 01:15:46,360
and division to try and quantify the value of an 
activity, which actually is about power laws. It's  

763
01:15:46,360 --> 01:15:54,440
not about that linear bullshit. It's really 
about power laws and non-linearities and all  

764
01:15:54,440 --> 01:16:01,000
this kind of stuff. And so we are being judged 
by the wrong maths. We're being evaluated by the  

765
01:16:01,000 --> 01:16:07,600
wrong maths and also we're being evaluated 
over the wrong timeframe. And consequently,  

766
01:16:07,600 --> 01:16:14,040
my argument would be that at a very rough 
estimate, an awful lot of marketing activity  

767
01:16:14,040 --> 01:16:20,800
is in reality four times as valuable. Four is, 
okay, I'm plucking that number out of the air,  

768
01:16:20,800 --> 01:16:26,760
but four seems about [inaudible 01:16:25] is 
probably four times as valuable as people think  

769
01:16:26,760 --> 01:16:32,240
it is when they measure its short-term 
contribution. Could be more of course

770
01:16:32,240 --> 01:16:37,200
I love that because over time it will build 
and it compounds. It's like a drip. I love  

771
01:16:37,200 --> 01:16:40,680
the three points you made about how 
to build a great brand consistency,  

772
01:16:40,680 --> 01:16:44,280
distinctiveness. What was 
the third? It was be famous?

773
01:16:44,280 --> 01:16:50,960
Yeah, consistency, 
distinctiveness, probably clarity.

774
01:16:50,960 --> 01:16:51,640
Clarity.

775
01:16:51,640 --> 01:16:53,040
Just be famous.

776
01:16:53,040 --> 01:16:53,360
Great.

777
01:16:53,360 --> 01:16:57,520
Yeah. Some sort of clarity of promise, I think.

778
01:16:57,520 --> 01:16:58,640
Amazing. Consistency-

779
01:16:58,640 --> 01:17:06,520
I think a good brand is a promise, but also 
the extent to which it contributes to trust,  

780
01:17:06,520 --> 01:17:16,160
which is that if you met a celebrity on the 
street, I don't mean a serial killer celebrity,  

781
01:17:16,160 --> 01:17:19,840
I mean a famous actor. One thing you 
wouldn't think about is are they going  

782
01:17:19,840 --> 01:17:24,600
to steal my wallet? Are they going to mug me? 
Are they going to do anything weird? They may  

783
01:17:24,600 --> 01:17:30,080
